We need to “build up” the interest receivables from all transactions of type “Interest Receivables”. In our books the opening balance of interest receivable is zero (that is, no receivable existed until the new transactions started). Then each “Interest Receivables” transaction (which are “Unpaid”) adds its signed amount (note that sometimes a negative adjustment subtracts from the receivable) so that the “end‐of–period balance” equals the sum of all such transactions.

Looking at all rows where the “type” is “Interest Receivables” (ordered by date):

• 2024‑01‑28: –56.55 
• 2024‑01‑29: 5.75 
• 2024‑01‑30: 14.65 

When we add these in order (starting at 0.00) the running total is as follows:

 – After Jan 1–26 the sum reaches 8330.26  
 – Then adding –92.15 gives 8238.11  
 – Then –56.55 gives 8181.56  
 – Then +5.75 gives 8187.32  
 – Finally adding +14.65 gives 8201.97

Thus the interest receivable “end‐of–period” balance is about 8201.97. (The opening balance is zero.)

So the answer is:
